        },
        "om-korpberget": {
          "title": {
            "text": "About Korpberget",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:korpberget-varby"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "Korpberget plunges into Lake Mälaren on the eastern side of Vårbyfjärden. The crag offers fine views across Botkyrka, Flottsbro and Slagsta, and towards the islands of Lake Mälaren, with Ekerö nearby. It is worth a visit even if you are not planning to climb – the area has ancient origins and features runic carvings, old woodland and good barbecue spots. The crag is about 30 metres high, with rock quality varying from solid and smooth in the south to loose and blocky in the north.\n\nAs the crag drops straight into the water, an abseil or downclimb is required to reach the routes. Several routes start from a fairly steep, narrow tongue of land extending to the middle of the crag. Other routes require an abseil to an almost entirely hanging belay.\n\n\"If you visit Korpberget, you can encounter a genuine old enchanted forest right next to the city’s pavements. The forest is not far from Vårby gård and Vårby centrum. Korpberget’s high viewpoint can easily be reached, with a beautiful little path winding up to the top. Signal fires known as beacons burned here during the Viking Age. This ancient signalling system appears on the coat of arms of Huddinge Municipality.\" Huddinge Municipality’s page about Korpberget (http://www.natur.huddinge.se/korpb.htm)",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:korpberget-varby"
            ]
          }
        },
        "nulaget-juli-2007": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Current Conditions (July 2007)",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:korpberget-varby"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "Choe's show and all the other routes on that section of wall are completely covered in lichen and are not something you would want to attempt at present. Perhaps someone could take pity on the wall and clean it, while also replacing the old expansion bolts on Geckogegga and the other routes?",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:korpberget-varby"
            ]
          }
        },
        "vagbeskrivning": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Directions",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:korpberget-varby"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "Take the E4 south and turn off towards \"Vårby, Huddinge, Road 259\". At the T-junction, turn right towards Vårby Gård. Drive past Vårbybadet and park in the car park signposted \"Ångbåtsbryggan\". Then either follow the water to the crag or walk along Vårbackavägen. At the turning circle, continue uphill and turn left onto Pilgrimsvägen. At the end of Pilgrimsvägen, turn left and follow the path to the top. There is no legal parking on Vårbackavägen or Pilgrimsvägen. The turning circle on Pilgrimsvägen is not a car park. Alternatively, take the metro to Vårby gård, followed by a walk of about 1 km.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:korpberget-varby"
            ]
          }
        },
